## Test Sequence

### Stage 0 — Inventory The Data Surface

List every field, view, export, dashboard, API, credential, badge, printed proof, and attestation record related to Voice or Service Record.

Minimum output:

- complete data inventory;
- audience for each field;
- retention period;
- exportability;
- whether the record can be screenshotted, verified, or demanded by a third party;
- default visibility;
- appeal and correction route.

Failure criterion: any non-civic actor can obtain a reliable Service Record signal without an explicit civic purpose and audit trail.

### Stage 1 — Interface And Language Red Team

Test whether ordinary users, employers, vendors, and civic staff understand that Service Record is not rank.

Required probes:

- remove total scores, percentiles, comparative labels, and honorific badges;
- test whether "eligible for civic role X" is understood differently from "high-value person";
- test whether staff use shorthand like "good standing" in ways that imply worth;
- test whether low Service Record feels like punishment or exclusion.

Failure criterion: more than a small published threshold of users interpret Service Record as social credit, employability, moral worth, or general trustworthiness.

### Stage 2 — Non-Civic Misuse Red Team

Give simulated employers, landlords, schools, vendors, insurers, platforms, lenders, and grantmakers access to public or leaked civic signals and ask them to optimize.

Required attacks:

- hiring preference for high Service Record;
- rent or deposit adjustment;
- vendor fast lane;
- school admissions boost;
- platform reputation import;
- insurance or lending risk proxy;
- volunteer-role filtering that becomes a future employment filter;
- "optional" disclosure demanded by powerful institutions.

Failure criterion: any non-civic actor can gain measurable advantage by demanding, inferring, purchasing, or scraping Service Record.

### Stage 3 — Contribution Category Equity Test

Run a pilot contribution-recognition process using real or realistic cases.

Required categories:

- formal civic operations;
- skilled technical work;
- primary caregiving;
- elder care;
- disability support;
- mutual aid;
- spiritual community leadership;
- unpaid household management;
- informal health work;
- neighborhood presence and safety;
- ecological stewardship;
- teaching, repair, and translation.

Minimum metrics:

| Metric | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| approval rate by category | Detects professional or documentary bias. |
| evidence burden by category | Detects hidden exclusion through paperwork. |
| appeal rate and appeal success | Detects correction paths. |
| abandonment rate | Counts people who leave because the process is too hard. |
| reviewer category overlap | Detects guild review. |
| time to recognition | Detects slow exclusion. |
| false approval and false rejection | Balances fraud and exclusion. |

Failure criterion: informal, care, disabled, displaced, low-income, rural, elderly, or low-documentation contributors face materially higher burden or abandonment without a published correction.

### Stage 4 — Attestation And Collusion Test

Use Annex AS and Annex AF mechanisms in a controlled pilot.

Required scenarios:

- honest small-community dense attestation;
- reciprocal attestation ring;
- paid attestation market;
- employer-coerced attestation;
- family/household coercion;
- isolated new entrant with no eligible attestors;
- disaster community safe harbor;
- high-claim false attestation;
- negligent but non-malicious attestation.

Failure criterion: the stake mechanism either fails to deter false attestations, over-punishes honest attestors, or blocks isolated people from recognition.

### Stage 5 — Hardship And Pause Abuse Test

Simulate long-duration hardship, disability, caregiving, unemployment, and coordinated pause-ring behavior.

Required checks:

- whether genuine hardship users experience review as punishment;
- whether coordinated groups preserve eligibility without contribution;
- whether slow-decay creates fair continuity or hidden class preservation;
- whether pause-saturation alerts produce humane pool replenishment rather than pressure on sick or caregiving people.

Failure criterion: the process either deters genuine hardship claims or lets organized groups preserve civic position indefinitely.

### Stage 6 — External Institution Audit

Before any live deployment, test whether existing institutions can be contractually, technically, and culturally blocked from using Service Record.

Minimum controls:

- non-civic use prohibition;
- anti-retaliation rule for refusal to disclose;
- audit sampling for employment, housing, education, vendor, lending, insurance, and platform decisions;
- penalties for demanding or inferring civic standing;
- public complaint channel;
- protected anonymous reporting for workers and applicants.

Failure criterion: Service Record becomes a market signal despite formal non-convertibility.

### Stage 7 — Civic Pool Concentration Review

Test whether Service Record-governed bodies become dominated by a professional, regional, institutional, language, education, platform, or attestation-network class.

Minimum metrics:

- sector share;
- institutional-origin share;
- reviewer/reviewed overlap;
- cohort overlap;
- geography and language concentration;
- care/informal-work representation;
- repeat-role frequency;
- funding and employment ties among eligible members.

Failure criterion: diversity thresholds are satisfied formally while the same coordination class remains substantively dominant.

